{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18693"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76855"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76855"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOsmoreceptors in the hypothalamus play a crucial role in maintaining body fluid homeostasis by monitoring plasma osmolality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how osmoreceptors detect changes in plasma osmolality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chemical receptor binding","Changes in cell volume","Direct ion channel activation","Neurotransmitter release detection","Membrane protein conformational changes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOsmoreceptors detect changes in plasma osmolality through \u003Cstrong\u003Echanges in cell volume\u003C/strong\u003E. When plasma osmolality increases, water moves out of the osmoreceptor cells causing them to shrink, which triggers mechanosensitive ion channels. This leads to increased neuronal firing, stimulating both thirst and vasopressin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect ion channel activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Changes in osmolality do not directly activate ion channels without first causing cell volume changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembrane protein conformational changes\u003C/strong\u003E - Osmoreceptors do not rely on direct protein shape changes to detect osmolality\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemical receptor binding\u003C/strong\u003E - There are no specific chemical receptors that bind to solutes to detect osmolality\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurotransmitter release detection\u003C/strong\u003E - Osmoreceptors respond directly to osmotic changes rather than detecting neurotransmitters\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe osmoreceptor response to cell volume changes is rapid and sensitive, allowing precise control of plasma osmolality within a narrow physiological range.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect changes in plasma osmolality by responding to cell volume changes.","When plasma osmolality increases, osmoreceptor cells shrink, triggering thirst and vasopressin release.","The primary osmoreceptors are located in the organum vasculosum of the lamina terminalis (OVLT) and subfornical organ."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:27:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:27:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76855"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}